Description: On November 3, 1944  venerated New Orleans jazz musician Don Albert opened the Keyhole Club at the intersection of Iowa and Pine streets  in the heart of San Antonio's predominantly African-American east side.

Opened in 1954, the Eastwood Country Club welcomed patrons of all races during a time of social unrest, uniting folks in the name of music, with many popular, well-known musical acts. The club, which hosted big-name acts such as Etta James, Nat "King" Cole, Ike & Tina Turner, and many more, was a great source of inspiration for young San Antonio musicians such as Spot Barnett, who later went on to make significant contributions to the Westside Sound as a saxophonist.

Conjunto musicians, and brothers, Rodolfo "Rudy T" Gonzalez and Manuel "Red" Gonzalez form "Rudy T and His Reno Bops", one of the early groups to pioneer the Westside Sound and influence Chicano Soul music.
Source:
"Biography: Rudy & The Reno Bops," American Sabor: Latinos in U.S.
Popular Music, http://americansabor.org/musicians/rudy-reno-bops
(accessed April 3, 2013).

Description: Rudy T and His Reno Bops record "Cry, Cry" in 1957 via Rio Records. With piano and horn elements, "Cry, Cry" demonstrates the early, formative style of the Westside Sound.

"Sunny Ozuna and Manny Guerra formed the Sunglows in 1958, a six-piece R&B combo composed of Mexican-American teenagers, most of whom attended Brackenridge High School." Other members included Jessie, Oscar, and Ray Villanueva; Tony Tostado, Gilbert Fernandez, Alfred Lunaand other mostly Chicano musicians throughout the group's existence.

Founded in 1959 by Joseph "Joe Anthony" Yanuzzi, Harlem Records "served as the initial catalyst in the career of one artist, Doug Sahm... But it also gave us outstanding vocal group records from the Lyrics, Royal Jesters, and Fabulous Flames, along with patented “West Side” R&B from Sunny and the Sunglows (before they were the Sunliners) and Charlie Alvarado and the Jives."

"Sunny and the Sunliners (as Sunny and the Sunglows) appeared on American Bandstand to promote their national hit single, “Talk to Me” in 1963. They were the first all-Tejano band to appear on the popular television show."
The phrase "The Westside Sound"  is coined and popularized by Dough Sahm through his release of the album, The Westside Sound Rolls Again.
Randy Garibay released the popular "Barbacoa Blues" album, with 10 tracks, including the iconic, "Barbacoa Blues" track that remains a staple in the San Antonio music community.
